        <tr>
          <td><strong>IV Antibiotic (per culture/sensitivity)</strong></td>
          <td>Varies — empiric broad-spectrum; targeted after culture results</td>
          <td>Collect wound culture BEFORE first dose. Administer per order — verify rate, concentration, compatibility. Monitor IV site for infiltration or phlebitis (change peripheral IV every 72–96 hours or per policy). Assess for allergic reaction — especially first dose; monitor 15–30 minutes after initiation. If vancomycin: infuse over ≥ 60 minutes (Red Man Syndrome risk with rapid infusion); monitor trough levels; assess renal function (nephrotoxicity).</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Analgesic (per order, PRN and scheduled)</strong></td>
          <td>Pain management (opioid and/or non-opioid per order)</td>
          <td>Pre-medicate <strong>30–60 minutes before wound care</strong> — inadequate pain management leads to patient avoidance and non-cooperation with care. Assess pain using 0–10 scale before and after administration. Monitor for opioid adverse effects: sedation, respiratory depression, constipation, urinary retention. Elderly patients (Agnes, 81 years) are more sensitive to opioids — start low, reassess frequently.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Nutritional Supplements (oral)</strong></td>
          <td>High-protein oral supplements; vitamin C; zinc</td>
          <td>Administer with meals or between meals per dietitian recommendation. Document intake accurately — report &lt; 50% consumed. Encourage high-protein foods: eggs, legumes, dairy, lean meat. Oral zinc supplement: take with food (reduces GI upset). Vitamin C supplement: supports collagen synthesis. Monitor albumin and prealbumin trends — prealbumin is the best short-term marker of nutritional repletion (half-life 2–3 days).</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Wound Care Supplies (topical)</strong></td>
          <td>Antimicrobial dressing (silver); absorbent dressing; normal saline irrigant</td>
          <td>Use sterile technique for all ORIF wound dressing changes. Silver-impregnated antimicrobial dressings release silver ions that inhibit bacterial growth — appropriate for infected wounds. Absorbent foam or alginate for heavily draining wounds. Change dressings per order frequency — typically every 24–48 hours for infected wounds or sooner if saturated. Always document wound appearance, drainage characteristics, and dressing type at each change.</td>
