  <!-- APPENDIX B: Q&A -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="appendix-b">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Appendix B</span>
      <h2>Post-Simulation Questions &amp; Answers</h2>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q1: What is the priority action when a surgical wound infection is suspected?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Obtain a wound culture BEFORE starting or changing antibiotics, then notify the provider.</strong> The sequence matters: (1) Perform wound assessment and document findings; (2) Collect wound culture using Levine technique after irrigating — before any new antibiotic dose; (3) Notify provider via SBAR with assessment findings; (4) Initiate ordered antibiotic therapy. Collecting the culture first ensures the sample reflects the true causative organism, allowing targeted antibiotic therapy rather than prolonged empiric broad-spectrum treatment.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q2: Why is Agnes particularly high-risk for wound infection complications?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Agnes has four compounding risk factors:</strong></p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Malnutrition:</strong> Impairs immune function (reduced neutrophil activity), collagen synthesis (protein + vitamin C deficiency), and epithelialization (vitamin A deficiency). Without adequate nutrition, neither the immune system nor the wound repair machinery can function effectively.</li>
          <li><strong>Advanced age (81 years):</strong> Immune senescence — reduced neutrophil chemotaxis and phagocytosis; thinner, more fragile skin; reduced inflammatory response; slower healing at the cellular level.</li>
          <li><strong>ORIF hardware:</strong> Metal plates and screws provide a surface for bacterial biofilm formation. Biofilm-protected organisms are up to 1,000× more resistant to antibiotics and immune cells — infection may require hardware removal to eradicate.</li>
          <li><strong>Immobility:</strong> Reduced perfusion to wound site, impaired lymphatic drainage, and increased pressure at bony prominences all promote bacterial colonization and impair healing.</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q3: Describe the correct wound culture technique (Levine method).</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Step-by-step Levine technique:</strong></p>
        <ol>
          <li>Irrigate wound with normal saline to remove surface contaminants and skin flora</li>
          <li>Allow irrigation to drain; gently blot with sterile gauze if needed</li>
          <li>Using a sterile swab, press firmly against a 1 cm² area of viable wound bed tissue</li>
          <li>Rotate the swab using firm pressure — this expresses tissue fluid from within the wound bed (NOT surface exudate)</li>
          <li>Place swab immediately in appropriate transport medium</li>
          <li>Label correctly; send to lab within 30 minutes</li>
          <li>Document time, technique, and wound appearance</li>
        </ol>
        <p><strong>Why NOT culture the exudate:</strong> Surface drainage contains colonizers and contaminants — not necessarily the organisms causing deep infection. The Levine technique samples the infecting organisms in viable tissue, providing clinically actionable culture results.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q4: What are the signs of early sepsis in an elderly patient and how do they differ from younger adults?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Classic early sepsis signs (qSOFA):</strong> Altered mental status; RR ≥ 22; SBP ≤ 100 mmHg. Also: fever &gt; 38°C or hypothermia &lt; 36°C; tachycardia &gt; 90 bpm; WBC &gt; 12,000 or &lt; 4,000/mm³.</p>
        <p><strong>How sepsis presents differently in elderly patients:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Confusion is often the first sign</strong> — elderly patients may not mount a fever or their fever may be blunted; new-onset confusion or worsening agitation can be the only early indicator</li>
          <li><strong>Hypothermia instead of fever</strong> — elderly and immunocompromised patients may have a <em>low</em> temperature despite serious infection (immune senescence impairs fever response)</li>
          <li><strong>Subtle tachycardia</strong> — elderly patients on beta-blockers or with cardiac conduction disease may not develop classic tachycardia even in the presence of infection</li>
          <li><strong>Falls</strong> — new or increased fall risk may signal hemodynamic compromise or altered mental status from early sepsis</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Clinical implication for Agnes:</strong> Assess baseline mental status at every interaction. Any new confusion, restlessness, or decreased responsiveness in Agnes requires urgent reassessment and provider notification — it may be the first sign that her wound infection is progressing to sepsis.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q5: How does malnutrition impair wound healing at the cellular level?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Four key cellular mechanisms:</strong></p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Collagen synthesis failure:</strong> Protein (amino acids), vitamin C, and zinc are all required for collagen cross-linking. Without them, fibroblasts cannot produce adequate collagen → wound cannot close → dehiscence risk increases.</li>
          <li><strong>Immune cell suppression:</strong> Protein deficiency reduces neutrophil production and phagocytic capacity → bacteria in the wound are not cleared → infection persists and deepens.</li>
          <li><strong>Edema and poor perfusion:</strong> Hypoalbuminemia (low serum albumin from protein malnutrition) reduces oncotic pressure → tissue edema → compressed microcirculation → inadequate O₂ delivery to healing cells.</li>
          <li><strong>Delayed epithelialization:</strong> Vitamin A deficiency impairs keratinocyte proliferation → the new skin layer cannot form over the healing wound → prolonged healing time with ongoing infection exposure.</li>
        </ol>
        <p><strong>Clinical bottom line:</strong> Without correcting Agnes's malnutrition, antibiotic therapy alone is unlikely to resolve the infection — her body lacks the biological tools to heal.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

